"{\"uid\": \"nbcsandiego.com-news-local-san-diego-skateboarder-2024-paris-olympics-3590934\", \"text\": \"Watch as Team USA skateboarder Tom Schaar wins silver in the men's park final.  The men's park skateboarding finals concluded Wednesday in Paris and San Diego was heavily represented.  Encinitas' Tom Schaar is taking home the silver in skateboarding park. The 24-year-old earned a 92.23 on his second run, the highest of his three runs to take home his first Olympic medal.  Stream San Diego News for free, 24/7, wherever you are with NBC 7.  Australia's Keegan Palmer, the defending champion from the Tokyo Games who was also born in San Diego, maintains his title with another gold win with a top score of 93.11. Brazil's Augusto Akio wins the bronze with 91.85.  Tate Carew, who went to Point Loma High School in San Diego, came in 5th place with a high score of 91.17.  Carew's best friend Gavin Bottger, of Oceanside, did not advance past the preliminary round.  San Diegans were watching their locals from home, including the owner of Rose Street Skate Shop, Sean Kelling. Kelling said the local skateboarding community is tight and there is much admiration for those who made it to the national stage.  \\\"If you got there, you did amazing. So, props to everyone who got involved,\\\" Kelling said. \\\"These are some of the greatest athletes in the world and sometimes they still can not land tricks. It's hard. So, you know, the feeling of landing something is - you can not take that, you can not explain that, you can not teach that until you actually do it. Even if it's just learning how to ollie. That first ollie will set you off.\\\"    Old dudes rule! Macdonald, Oberholzer compete at Olympics\"}"